WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.280 --> 00:00:06.240
RETO MEIER: Hi there.

00:00:06.240 --> 00:00:06.930
My name is Reto Meier.

00:00:06.930 --> 00:00:08.950
IAN NI-LEWIS: And I'm
Ian Ni-Lewis.

00:00:08.950 --> 00:00:11.230
RETO MEIER: This week, we find
out what's up with SMS

00:00:11.230 --> 00:00:13.220
replacement app, WhatsApp
Messenger.

00:00:13.220 --> 00:00:15.680
IAN NI-LEWIS: We take a bite out
of the Group Me 4 beta, to

00:00:15.680 --> 00:00:17.480
see if we like the new flavor.

00:00:17.480 --> 00:00:19.480
RETO MEIER: Turns out it tastes
a lot less like fruit

00:00:19.480 --> 00:00:20.070
than it used to.

00:00:20.070 --> 00:00:21.320
IAN NI-LEWIS: And a lot
more like ice cream.

00:00:21.320 --> 00:00:23.310
RETO MEIER: And we discover that
instant messaging classic

00:00:23.310 --> 00:00:26.560
Trillian has not only survived
the apocalyptic instant

00:00:26.560 --> 00:00:29.600
messaging wars of the early
2000s, but has risen from the

00:00:29.600 --> 00:00:31.830
ashes to flourish in
the mobile space.

00:00:31.830 --> 00:00:32.940
IAN NI-LEWIS: All that
and more, this

00:00:32.940 --> 00:00:37.930
week on The App Clinic.

00:00:40.990 --> 00:00:42.680
RETO MEIER: This week, we're
looking at instant messaging

00:00:42.680 --> 00:00:45.370
apps, which turns out to be a
critical part of mine and

00:00:45.370 --> 00:00:46.370
Ian's teamwork flow.

00:00:46.370 --> 00:00:46.740
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah.

00:00:46.740 --> 00:00:49.450
What you may not realize is
Reto and I never speak

00:00:49.450 --> 00:00:50.340
directly to one another.

00:00:50.340 --> 00:00:51.710
IAN NI-LEWIS: In fact,
we don't even ever

00:00:51.710 --> 00:00:52.780
be in the same room.

00:00:52.780 --> 00:00:53.900
We're actually on opposite
sides of

00:00:53.900 --> 00:00:55.080
building 44 right now.

00:00:55.080 --> 00:00:55.590
IAN NI-LEWIS: That's right.

00:00:55.590 --> 00:00:58.440
Reto's not here at all.

00:00:58.440 --> 00:01:00.390
So that means IM apps
are critical for us

00:01:00.390 --> 00:01:01.370
to get things done.

00:01:01.370 --> 00:01:05.010
RETO MEIER: Let's start by
looking at WhatsApp.

00:01:05.010 --> 00:01:06.610
IAN NI-LEWIS: WhatsApp Messenger
was by far our most

00:01:06.610 --> 00:01:07.830
popular candidate this
week, right?

00:01:07.830 --> 00:01:08.700
RETO MEIER: Absolutely, yeah.

00:01:08.700 --> 00:01:11.140
And you can see here that
they've done a pretty good job

00:01:11.140 --> 00:01:14.030
on their landing page
on Google Play.

00:01:14.030 --> 00:01:16.010
It's one of the things that
they've done a little bit

00:01:16.010 --> 00:01:18.010
wrong here is they've got a
great logo, which I really

00:01:18.010 --> 00:01:18.710
like to see.

00:01:18.710 --> 00:01:20.570
But what they've done which
I think they could really

00:01:20.570 --> 00:01:22.850
improve on is their feature
graphic, which is effectively

00:01:22.850 --> 00:01:25.910
just a combination of their
logo, the app name, and a

00:01:25.910 --> 00:01:26.892
bunch of screenshots.

00:01:26.892 --> 00:01:29.615
Now, it turns out that there are
other places on the Google

00:01:29.615 --> 00:01:33.410
Play listing for your logo, app
name, and screenshots, and

00:01:33.410 --> 00:01:35.170
so it's kind of a
waste of space.

00:01:35.170 --> 00:01:37.050
So they've done the right thing
in having a feature

00:01:37.050 --> 00:01:38.455
graphic, but they could
do a lot more with

00:01:38.455 --> 00:01:39.550
what they've got.

00:01:39.550 --> 00:01:40.560
IAN NI-LEWIS: Sure.

00:01:40.560 --> 00:01:43.090
RETO MEIER: So what
is this app?

00:01:43.090 --> 00:01:46.500
It describes itself as a super
powered replacement for SMS

00:01:46.500 --> 00:01:47.920
messaging, and I'd say
it pretty much

00:01:47.920 --> 00:01:49.400
lives up to that claim.

00:01:49.400 --> 00:01:52.060
It can do all of the regular
instant messaging type

00:01:52.060 --> 00:01:54.750
behavior that you expect, which
is basically sending

00:01:54.750 --> 00:01:57.490
instant messages to other
people, all without having to

00:01:57.490 --> 00:02:01.420
rely on a cell network
connection in order to do so.

00:02:01.420 --> 00:02:03.630
So the big plus here is that if
you don't have an unlimited

00:02:03.630 --> 00:02:06.500
text messaging plan, you can
send messages to your friends

00:02:06.500 --> 00:02:10.250
at no cost, which is nice.

00:02:10.250 --> 00:02:12.450
As a bonus, you can also
do multimedia stuff.

00:02:12.450 --> 00:02:15.430
So you can send pictures,
images, videos, movies, all of

00:02:15.430 --> 00:02:19.900
that sort of stuff, which you
can theoretically do with MMS,

00:02:19.900 --> 00:02:21.320
but this makes it
a lot easier.

00:02:21.320 --> 00:02:23.490
And of course, it also supports
offline messaging,

00:02:23.490 --> 00:02:25.240
which is nice.

00:02:25.240 --> 00:02:27.260
They try and keep things as
simple as possible by tying

00:02:27.260 --> 00:02:29.040
everything into your phone
number rather than having a

00:02:29.040 --> 00:02:31.895
secondary account, which is
nice, but it does mean that

00:02:31.895 --> 00:02:33.820
you can't use this app
on tablet devices.

00:02:33.820 --> 00:02:35.670
And sure enough, they've
actually blocked installation

00:02:35.670 --> 00:02:40.350
for those platforms, which is
a little bit disappointing,

00:02:40.350 --> 00:02:42.050
frankly, because it
really does limit

00:02:42.050 --> 00:02:43.080
the utility the app.

00:02:43.080 --> 00:02:44.780
And given that it's transferring
data over the

00:02:44.780 --> 00:02:47.770
internet, why force me to depend
on having a mobile

00:02:47.770 --> 00:02:51.470
number and having a device
with a mobile connection?

00:02:51.470 --> 00:02:53.680
So as you can see from this
screenshot, I think WhatsApp

00:02:53.680 --> 00:02:56.320
Messenger could really do with
a full UI overhaul, really

00:02:56.320 --> 00:02:58.350
bringing it up to date with
whole new themes, and

00:02:58.350 --> 00:03:01.030
genuinely presenting a more
consistent and intuitive UI

00:03:01.030 --> 00:03:02.600
navigation structure.

00:03:02.600 --> 00:03:04.480
I'm not going to get too
much detail into that.

00:03:04.480 --> 00:03:06.060
That's kind of Roman's
wheelhouse, so I'm going to

00:03:06.060 --> 00:03:08.210
let him and the guys comment
more on that aspect on

00:03:08.210 --> 00:03:09.410
Tuesday's Android Design
In Action.

00:03:09.410 --> 00:03:11.040
IAN NI-LEWIS: But I think
we do have to say that

00:03:11.040 --> 00:03:11.730
[INAUDIBLE]

00:03:11.730 --> 00:03:15.960
is fine, but it's pretty old
school to just slap some sort

00:03:15.960 --> 00:03:19.565
of random picture behind
your stuff.

00:03:19.565 --> 00:03:20.080
RETO MEIER: Absolutely.

00:03:20.080 --> 00:03:21.630
I mean, if you're using
[INAUDIBLE]

00:03:21.630 --> 00:03:24.700
as a technique to try and make
users more comfortable with

00:03:24.700 --> 00:03:26.300
the app so that they feel
more familiar with the

00:03:26.300 --> 00:03:28.580
expectations, then that's
a great idea.

00:03:28.580 --> 00:03:31.480
Here, it just looks like, eh,
white and black backgrounds

00:03:31.480 --> 00:03:32.310
look kind of boring.

00:03:32.310 --> 00:03:33.400
Let's stick something behind.

00:03:33.400 --> 00:03:34.700
Maybe a faux rock effect.

00:03:34.700 --> 00:03:37.560
And frankly, that doesn't
really add to it.

00:03:37.560 --> 00:03:39.500
It just makes the whole thing
look a little bit untidy.

00:03:39.500 --> 00:03:41.880
IAN NI-LEWIS: True.

00:03:41.880 --> 00:03:44.420
So the elevator pitch for Group
Me is that it's like

00:03:44.420 --> 00:03:45.660
your own private Twitter.

00:03:45.660 --> 00:03:47.495
And I think that's a pretty
accurate description.

00:03:52.210 --> 00:03:52.900
Awesome.

00:03:52.900 --> 00:03:53.400
MALE SPEAKER: My fault.

00:03:53.400 --> 00:03:54.490
Sorry.

00:03:54.490 --> 00:03:55.940
IAN NI-LEWIS: No, no,
no, it's cool.

00:03:55.940 --> 00:03:57.140
Take your time.

00:03:57.140 --> 00:03:58.130
All right.

00:03:58.130 --> 00:04:00.130
We've used Group Me a lot
on the Android team.

00:04:00.130 --> 00:04:02.330
When we go to a conference like
Google I/O, it's tough to

00:04:02.330 --> 00:04:04.020
stay in sync with
the whole team.

00:04:04.020 --> 00:04:06.770
And if you don't stay in touch,
well, you miss things

00:04:06.770 --> 00:04:10.110
like the $100 shots of Glen
Ross that Dan Galpin

00:04:10.110 --> 00:04:12.380
missed at I/O 2012.

00:04:12.380 --> 00:04:13.950
That was a good night.

00:04:13.950 --> 00:04:15.400
And thanks, Dan.

00:04:15.400 --> 00:04:17.500
We will pay you back someday.

00:04:17.500 --> 00:04:20.300
Anyway, Group Me isn't perfect,
but so far, it's been

00:04:20.300 --> 00:04:23.190
the most reliable solution for
keeping our group in sync.

00:04:23.190 --> 00:04:25.690
It works via push messaging, but
it can also send messages

00:04:25.690 --> 00:04:29.900
via SMS, so it works even if
you don't have a data plan.

00:04:29.900 --> 00:04:32.380
That's pretty important if
you're in Shanghai or

00:04:32.380 --> 00:04:34.840
Barcelona or Sao Polo.

00:04:34.840 --> 00:04:36.330
RETO MEIER: Or the I280 between

00:04:36.330 --> 00:04:37.250
Cupertino and Sunnyvale.

00:04:37.250 --> 00:04:37.810
IAN NI-LEWIS: Well,
that's true.

00:04:37.810 --> 00:04:38.040
Yeah.

00:04:38.040 --> 00:04:41.050
There's some sort of rip in
the fabric of reality down

00:04:41.050 --> 00:04:43.880
there that disturbs anything
that gets too close.

00:04:43.880 --> 00:04:47.910
Speaking of which, Group Me used
to look like this, which

00:04:47.910 --> 00:04:51.490
made it feel a lot less
like an Android app.

00:04:51.490 --> 00:04:53.310
The speech bubbles not only
make me feel like I've

00:04:53.310 --> 00:04:56.310
accidentally picked up someone
else's device--

00:04:56.310 --> 00:04:58.400
some hipster's device--

00:04:58.400 --> 00:05:01.410
they also waste space and clash
with the Android action

00:05:01.410 --> 00:05:03.870
bar at the top of the screen.

00:05:03.870 --> 00:05:06.100
So the redesign is a better use
of space and feels a lot

00:05:06.100 --> 00:05:07.320
more like Android.

00:05:07.320 --> 00:05:09.520
It's even got some nice touches
like the embedded map

00:05:09.520 --> 00:05:11.200
view, and that's great
for finding out

00:05:11.200 --> 00:05:12.060
where the party is.

00:05:12.060 --> 00:05:14.730
In fact, I remember in
Barcelona, we were trying to

00:05:14.730 --> 00:05:18.280
find the party for, gee,
how long was it, Dan?

00:05:18.280 --> 00:05:19.520
It was like, hours, right?

00:05:19.520 --> 00:05:20.890
MALE SPEAKER: We walked
around for hours.

00:05:20.890 --> 00:05:22.400
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah, and
we couldn't find it.

00:05:22.400 --> 00:05:24.350
RETO MEIER: But in Barcelona,
everywhere's a party.

00:05:24.350 --> 00:05:26.200
Like, just open the
nearest door.

00:05:26.200 --> 00:05:27.750
IAN NI-LEWIS: That is true,
but we were looking for a

00:05:27.750 --> 00:05:29.270
specific party.

00:05:29.270 --> 00:05:31.170
MALE SPEAKER: The
great ragers.

00:05:31.170 --> 00:05:32.360
IAN NI-LEWIS: We didn't
want to get fired.

00:05:32.360 --> 00:05:33.320
Let's put it that way.

00:05:33.320 --> 00:05:35.090
RETO MEIER: You didn't want to
be like Dan and miss out on

00:05:35.090 --> 00:05:36.250
the free booze.

00:05:36.250 --> 00:05:37.810
IAN NI-LEWIS: Exactly.

00:05:37.810 --> 00:05:40.840
Well, my only objection to the
redesign is the way they've

00:05:40.840 --> 00:05:42.340
changed the action bar.

00:05:42.340 --> 00:05:44.820
Group Me has jumped on
the drawer bandwagon.

00:05:44.820 --> 00:05:46.990
So not only did they take
away the regular

00:05:46.990 --> 00:05:47.660
[? app affordance, ?]

00:05:47.660 --> 00:05:51.330
but they've also got this three
bar thing that I guess

00:05:51.330 --> 00:05:55.860
is starting to be acknowledged
as the universal drawer

00:05:55.860 --> 00:05:59.030
pattern, but I'm still a fan of
the [? app affordance. ?]

00:05:59.030 --> 00:06:02.040
And apparently they didn't get
the memo about the design

00:06:02.040 --> 00:06:04.500
guidelines for drawers.

00:06:04.500 --> 00:06:08.240
Just in case you're in the same
boat, here is the memo.

00:06:08.240 --> 00:06:10.740
The main takeaway is that
drawers should slide out under

00:06:10.740 --> 00:06:13.480
the action bar, not push the
action bar out of the way.

00:06:13.480 --> 00:06:16.700
That's important, because your
action bar still needs to be

00:06:16.700 --> 00:06:19.670
contextual, it's still your
[? app affordance. ?]

00:06:19.670 --> 00:06:23.450
We don't want it to arbitrarily
leave the screen.

00:06:23.450 --> 00:06:25.170
But let's not get too caught
up in the design.

00:06:25.170 --> 00:06:26.650
That's really Roman's job.

00:06:26.650 --> 00:06:28.185
Let's go ahead and move on.

00:06:31.800 --> 00:06:33.630
Overall, the beta looks
like Group Me is

00:06:33.630 --> 00:06:35.200
moving in a great direction.

00:06:35.200 --> 00:06:37.860
I love the way they've
worked with media.

00:06:37.860 --> 00:06:41.620
A lot of the recommendations
that we've given about using

00:06:41.620 --> 00:06:45.780
larger pictures and alpha text
over the pictures just make it

00:06:45.780 --> 00:06:47.790
look fantastic.

00:06:47.790 --> 00:06:51.560
Honestly, the only thing that
I really, really wish that

00:06:51.560 --> 00:06:55.340
Group Me did is an
easier login.

00:06:55.340 --> 00:06:58.700
Now, they've actually made a
big change for the better.

00:06:58.700 --> 00:07:01.310
In the previous version, you had
to login with your phone

00:07:01.310 --> 00:07:06.220
number, which, for me,
was a horrible issue.

00:07:06.220 --> 00:07:11.500
Not only do I use Google Voice
and have like 10 different

00:07:11.500 --> 00:07:12.770
SIMs that I use--

00:07:12.770 --> 00:07:15.530
I can never remember which phone
number I actually logged

00:07:15.530 --> 00:07:17.050
into Group Me with first.

00:07:17.050 --> 00:07:20.280
I think it was something that I
threw away a long time ago.

00:07:20.280 --> 00:07:26.370
But their SMS permission system,
where they'll send you

00:07:26.370 --> 00:07:28.660
a text to say, is this
really your phone?

00:07:28.660 --> 00:07:31.280
It doesn't always work,
and I don't know why.

00:07:31.280 --> 00:07:32.870
RETO MEIER: I had that problem
today, actually.

00:07:32.870 --> 00:07:33.300
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah.

00:07:33.300 --> 00:07:35.430
It might be that because of
their beta, the servers are

00:07:35.430 --> 00:07:36.840
just under load or something.

00:07:36.840 --> 00:07:39.840
Anyway, they made it so you can
log in with a username and

00:07:39.840 --> 00:07:41.790
password, but if you've been
watching the show, you know

00:07:41.790 --> 00:07:43.370
what my pet peeve is here.

00:07:43.370 --> 00:07:45.810
Don't make me type in a
username and password.

00:07:45.810 --> 00:07:48.720
My credentials are
on the phone.

00:07:48.720 --> 00:07:54.260
Either put the account on the
phone, or synchronize or

00:07:54.260 --> 00:07:57.440
federate with an account
that's already there.

00:07:57.440 --> 00:07:59.000
Google Play services
makes this easy.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:01.460
We talked about that
a couple weeks ago.

00:08:01.460 --> 00:08:04.360
Typing in passwords
is so 2010.

00:08:04.360 --> 00:08:05.990
Don't make me do it.

00:08:05.990 --> 00:08:08.320
All right, let's go
ahead and move on.

00:08:08.320 --> 00:08:08.750
RETO MEIER: All right.

00:08:08.750 --> 00:08:11.380
So I think the biggest surprise
for me with Trillian

00:08:11.380 --> 00:08:14.600
is that it actually still
existed, and I mean that as

00:08:14.600 --> 00:08:15.360
kind of a compliment.

00:08:15.360 --> 00:08:17.490
It's great to see a company able
to leverage their core

00:08:17.490 --> 00:08:19.880
strengths and really take
advantage of new opportunities

00:08:19.880 --> 00:08:21.120
when they arrive.

00:08:21.120 --> 00:08:24.230
And that's really exactly what
the team at Trillian has done.

00:08:24.230 --> 00:08:26.730
So in the height of the instant
messaging federation

00:08:26.730 --> 00:08:29.410
wars, Trillian was my go to
client for being able to

00:08:29.410 --> 00:08:31.000
connect to multiple
services at once.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:34.289
I was on ICQ, I had friends
who were on--

00:08:34.289 --> 00:08:35.275
what other ones existed?

00:08:35.275 --> 00:08:36.210
Yahoo?

00:08:36.210 --> 00:08:36.679
I don't know.

00:08:36.679 --> 00:08:36.990
There was a bunch.

00:08:36.990 --> 00:08:37.640
IAN NI-LEWIS: AOL.

00:08:37.640 --> 00:08:37.880
RETO MEIER: AOL.

00:08:37.880 --> 00:08:38.100
Yeah.

00:08:38.100 --> 00:08:39.450
There was heaps of them.

00:08:39.450 --> 00:08:42.510
And so Trillian was a great way
to have one app that lived

00:08:42.510 --> 00:08:46.170
on my desktop PC at that time
that let me communicate with

00:08:46.170 --> 00:08:49.120
everyone, because that was the
only way we could get things

00:08:49.120 --> 00:08:52.110
done was to have clients do
the federation for us.

00:08:52.110 --> 00:08:54.030
Now, these days, they've taken
it a step further, and they've

00:08:54.030 --> 00:08:56.820
added support for some of the
newer protocols like Facebook

00:08:56.820 --> 00:08:59.690
instant messaging, I think Skype
is either there or on

00:08:59.690 --> 00:09:00.760
their roadmap.

00:09:00.760 --> 00:09:02.670
And of course, with most of
these conversations now

00:09:02.670 --> 00:09:05.150
happening from people's phones,
it's great to see

00:09:05.150 --> 00:09:07.300
Trillian offering
a mobile app.

00:09:07.300 --> 00:09:10.700
So rather than being a
replacement for SMS messaging

00:09:10.700 --> 00:09:14.450
like the two apps that we looked
at earlier, Trillian is

00:09:14.450 --> 00:09:16.850
really looking to replace the
need for having a number of

00:09:16.850 --> 00:09:19.860
separate chat clients for each
different services that you

00:09:19.860 --> 00:09:20.980
already use.

00:09:20.980 --> 00:09:24.120
So it's supposed to replace
having to have four or five

00:09:24.120 --> 00:09:26.540
different instant messaging
clients.

00:09:26.540 --> 00:09:29.440
And they've done a great job of
keeping things simple, and

00:09:29.440 --> 00:09:30.790
you can see that on the
screenshot here.

00:09:30.790 --> 00:09:34.190
And as you go through the app,
it really is sort of that cut

00:09:34.190 --> 00:09:36.560
down, most basic vision of
how instant messaging

00:09:36.560 --> 00:09:37.450
apps used to work.

00:09:37.450 --> 00:09:41.210
You have a list of contacts, in
this case separated by the

00:09:41.210 --> 00:09:44.290
service type, so you can see
who your ICQ friends are--

00:09:44.290 --> 00:09:47.340
which kind of doesn't make that
much sense, because I

00:09:47.340 --> 00:09:50.610
don't really care what
technology I'm using, what

00:09:50.610 --> 00:09:53.240
back end service I'm using to
communicate with people.

00:09:53.240 --> 00:09:55.570
I just want to see the people
and communicate with them.

00:09:55.570 --> 00:09:58.090
And I guess the complexity here
is that often people will

00:09:58.090 --> 00:10:00.700
have multiple accounts on each
of the different services, so

00:10:00.700 --> 00:10:02.570
how do you reconcile that?

00:10:02.570 --> 00:10:04.160
I think that's one of the
challenges, and something

00:10:04.160 --> 00:10:07.070
