00:15:26.450 --> 00:15:28.250
RETO MEIER: Well, I think it's
also worth discussing how

00:15:28.250 --> 00:15:30.950
these instant messaging
apps actually work.

00:15:30.950 --> 00:15:33.630
The key to a great experience
is really balancing that low

00:15:33.630 --> 00:15:37.670
latency instant instant
messaging with making sure

00:15:37.670 --> 00:15:40.180
that you're not draining the
battery in order to get those

00:15:40.180 --> 00:15:41.540
rapid updates.

00:15:41.540 --> 00:15:43.810
So fundamentally, there's a
couple of different approaches

00:15:43.810 --> 00:15:45.115
that you can take.

00:15:45.115 --> 00:15:47.840
On the first hand, you can
maintain an open socket

00:15:47.840 --> 00:15:50.820
connection between your client
running on each device and

00:15:50.820 --> 00:15:52.050
your server.

00:15:52.050 --> 00:15:54.610
Now, having an open socket will
minimize your latency,

00:15:54.610 --> 00:15:55.910
because the connection
is there.

00:15:55.910 --> 00:15:57.700
You can just send stuff
through that pipe.

00:15:57.700 --> 00:15:59.820
But you really need to carefully
manage it so that

00:15:59.820 --> 00:16:02.120
you're not draining your battery
exceptionally quickly

00:16:02.120 --> 00:16:04.110
by maintaining that socket.

00:16:04.110 --> 00:16:06.870
So the way that you actually
keep the socket open is by

00:16:06.870 --> 00:16:08.550
sending data or sending
[INAUDIBLE]

00:16:08.550 --> 00:16:11.680
pings to your server at regular
intervals, which is

00:16:11.680 --> 00:16:13.230
going to stop the network
from automatically

00:16:13.230 --> 00:16:14.900
closing those sockets.

00:16:14.900 --> 00:16:16.740
But if you ping too regularly,
you're just going to be

00:16:16.740 --> 00:16:18.340
keeping the cell radio
turned on.

00:16:18.340 --> 00:16:20.070
It's just going to drain
the battery.

00:16:20.070 --> 00:16:21.950
And if you do it too
infrequently, you're going to

00:16:21.950 --> 00:16:23.360
lose your socket connection
anyway.

00:16:23.360 --> 00:16:25.440
So the latency's going to go up,
because you're expecting

00:16:25.440 --> 00:16:27.120
it to be zero latency,
but it isn't.

00:16:27.120 --> 00:16:29.320
You've got the additional cost
it takes to initiate a new

00:16:29.320 --> 00:16:30.050
socket connection.

00:16:30.050 --> 00:16:32.165
It's just a bad time
all around.

00:16:32.165 --> 00:16:35.530
And figuring out the right
frequency is actually really,

00:16:35.530 --> 00:16:36.940
really hard.

00:16:36.940 --> 00:16:38.780
It varies between network
operators--

00:16:38.780 --> 00:16:40.760
the sockets that you're allowed
to use to have these

00:16:40.760 --> 00:16:43.610
long, looped connections vary
depending on networks.

00:16:43.610 --> 00:16:46.660
So it makes it really difficult
for individual app

00:16:46.660 --> 00:16:47.850
developers to figure out.

00:16:47.850 --> 00:16:50.280
And frankly, that's not the sort
of thing that you want to

00:16:50.280 --> 00:16:51.480
have to be thinking about.

00:16:51.480 --> 00:16:54.640
You want to be focusing on
features, on UI, not how do I

00:16:54.640 --> 00:16:57.620
keep the data connection going
between the app and server.

00:16:57.620 --> 00:16:59.640
IAN NI-LEWIS: You know, not only
that, but even if you got

00:16:59.640 --> 00:17:04.420
everything right, in order to
avoid draining the battery and

00:17:04.420 --> 00:17:06.420
keep the socket open and get
all the behavior that you

00:17:06.420 --> 00:17:09.349
want, you would also have to
synchronize perfectly with any

00:17:09.349 --> 00:17:11.319
other app that wanted
to do this, right?

00:17:11.319 --> 00:17:15.270
Because even if-- let's say 10
minutes is the magic number.

00:17:15.270 --> 00:17:17.484
My app goes every 10
minutes, your app

00:17:17.484 --> 00:17:18.680
goes every 10 minutes.

00:17:18.680 --> 00:17:20.780
Your app started five
minutes after mine.

00:17:20.780 --> 00:17:21.400
Ouch.

00:17:21.400 --> 00:17:22.910
RETO MEIER: Whoopsie.

00:17:22.910 --> 00:17:24.460
So can we do that, then?

00:17:24.460 --> 00:17:27.514
How can we synchronize all of
the apps on the device so that

00:17:27.514 --> 00:17:29.860
they all send pings
at the same time?

00:17:29.860 --> 00:17:30.990
IAN NI-LEWIS: Well, I think
you've got to have somebody

00:17:30.990 --> 00:17:32.310
send the pings for you.

00:17:32.310 --> 00:17:32.810
RETO MEIER: Exactly.

00:17:32.810 --> 00:17:35.120
And happily, that is
exactly what Google

00:17:35.120 --> 00:17:36.210
Cloud Messaging does.

00:17:36.210 --> 00:17:38.220
So we've already figured out
the most efficient way to

00:17:38.220 --> 00:17:41.870
maintain a low latency network
path, and in fact, this is

00:17:41.870 --> 00:17:44.580
something that we can keep
track of and continue to

00:17:44.580 --> 00:17:47.470
optimize and make more and more
efficient, so that you

00:17:47.470 --> 00:17:49.350
can just piggyback on top
of that, and use it as a

00:17:49.350 --> 00:17:52.400
mechanism to tell your app when
it should initiate a new

00:17:52.400 --> 00:17:55.090
connection and start
transferring those

00:17:55.090 --> 00:17:56.330
messages in real time.

00:17:56.330 --> 00:17:59.640
So all the details for Google
Cloud Messaging are available

00:17:59.640 --> 00:18:02.930
on that cloud sync Android
training class.

00:18:02.930 --> 00:18:05.850
So the thing is, though, that
cloud to device messaging or

00:18:05.850 --> 00:18:08.640
C2DM, as we like to call it,
because everyone loves an

00:18:08.640 --> 00:18:11.560
acronym, doesn't guarantee
the delivery latency.

00:18:11.560 --> 00:18:13.930
It will definitely get there,
but you don't know that it'll

00:18:13.930 --> 00:18:15.680
get there straight away.

00:18:15.680 --> 00:18:18.360
Now, chances are it will get
there straight away.

00:18:18.360 --> 00:18:21.910
But one approach, too, is
actually use C2DM to initiate

00:18:21.910 --> 00:18:22.660
the conversation.

00:18:22.660 --> 00:18:26.200
So when someone pings you with
a message the first time, use

00:18:26.200 --> 00:18:29.250
see C2DM to notify the
recipient, who can then create

00:18:29.250 --> 00:18:31.620
a short lived socket connection
to transfer the

00:18:31.620 --> 00:18:33.535
rapid fire messages backwards
and forwards.

00:18:33.535 --> 00:18:36.510
So then you're just keeping
a short lived socket.

00:18:36.510 --> 00:18:38.620
You kill it as soon as the
conversation is finished, and

00:18:38.620 --> 00:18:43.350
then fall back to waiting for
C2DM to wake up your app and

00:18:43.350 --> 00:18:45.190
listen for new messages.

00:18:45.190 --> 00:18:50.090
So some apps that we looked at
actually chose to use a third

00:18:50.090 --> 00:18:52.580
option, which isn't really
an option, which

00:18:52.580 --> 00:18:55.040
is polling the server--

00:18:55.040 --> 00:18:56.520
just pinging your server to
check to see whether you've

00:18:56.520 --> 00:18:57.840
got any new messages pending.

00:18:57.840 --> 00:19:00.960
And that's kind of a terrible
idea, because the latency is

00:19:00.960 --> 00:19:02.880
going to be shocking, unless
you're doing it every minute,

00:19:02.880 --> 00:19:05.080
in which case the battery drain
is going to be even more

00:19:05.080 --> 00:19:06.240
shocking than the latency.

00:19:06.240 --> 00:19:10.700
And I saw some comments in
reviews suggesting that that's

00:19:10.700 --> 00:19:16.850
what WhatsApp Messenger does
to get its messages.

00:19:16.850 --> 00:19:18.700
I haven't confirmed that, so I
don't want to criticize them

00:19:18.700 --> 00:19:20.180
too sharply without knowing
for certain.

00:19:20.180 --> 00:19:22.550
But if that is the case, then
that's definitely something

00:19:22.550 --> 00:19:26.790
you want to move away from and
move towards a GCM model.

00:19:26.790 --> 00:19:29.910
So if you have your own service,
polling is never the

00:19:29.910 --> 00:19:30.960
right answer.

00:19:30.960 --> 00:19:33.570
So if you're relying on someone
else's service to get

00:19:33.570 --> 00:19:36.580
information so you can't send a
push message, well, OK, then

00:19:36.580 --> 00:19:38.730
you're going to have to come
up with something clever.

00:19:38.730 --> 00:19:41.190
But if you've got your own
servers, then this is going to

00:19:41.190 --> 00:19:43.380
make your life a lot easier.

00:19:43.380 --> 00:19:43.880
So yes.

00:19:43.880 --> 00:19:44.700
Switch to GCM.

00:19:44.700 --> 00:19:47.110
The sun will shine brighter,
food will taste sweeter, and

00:19:47.110 --> 00:19:49.870
life will always be better.

00:19:49.870 --> 00:19:52.110
IAN NI-LEWIS: I switched
to GCM.

00:19:52.110 --> 00:19:55.830
I liked it so much I
