00:20:35.950 --> 00:20:37.720
a richer experience talking
to more than one

00:20:37.720 --> 00:20:40.140
person using a tablet.

00:20:40.140 --> 00:20:42.860
IAN NI-LEWIS: I was surprised at
how common it was for some

00:20:42.860 --> 00:20:47.660
of these messaging apps to rely
on SMS if not as their

00:20:47.660 --> 00:20:49.700
only transport mechanism,
then at least as

00:20:49.700 --> 00:20:51.030
their primary mechanism.

00:20:51.030 --> 00:20:54.110
And that really feels
like five years ago.

00:20:54.110 --> 00:20:54.830
RETO MEIER: It does.

00:20:54.830 --> 00:20:59.250
It kind of made sense back when,
hey, we can simplify

00:20:59.250 --> 00:21:01.990
signup by just checking what
the phone number is.

00:21:01.990 --> 00:21:04.500
But now it actually complicates
it, because half

00:21:04.500 --> 00:21:08.650
of my devices don't have
a SIM card in them.

00:21:08.650 --> 00:21:11.880
I've got tablets, I've got some
devices without SIMs, so

00:21:11.880 --> 00:21:13.410
it really just makes
my life harder.

00:21:13.410 --> 00:21:16.990
So a non-phone signup flow for
WhatsApp Messenger would make

00:21:16.990 --> 00:21:18.560
my life a lot better.

00:21:18.560 --> 00:21:20.410
I'd love to see a
modernized UI.

00:21:20.410 --> 00:21:23.250
I'd love to see some using cloud
to device messaging, if

00:21:23.250 --> 00:21:26.230
they're not already doing so.

00:21:26.230 --> 00:21:27.170
Yeah.

00:21:27.170 --> 00:21:28.650
IAN NI-LEWIS: In the
future, none of us

00:21:28.650 --> 00:21:30.310
will have phone numbers.

00:21:30.310 --> 00:21:32.690
You're going to be able to
ring my email address.

00:21:32.690 --> 00:21:33.820
RETO MEIER: I would
like to do that.

00:21:33.820 --> 00:21:36.260
That would make me
a happier person.

00:21:36.260 --> 00:21:38.420
What did you think
about Group Me?

00:21:38.420 --> 00:21:42.040
IAN NI-LEWIS: Well, Group Me is
in beta, and the beta looks

00:21:42.040 --> 00:21:43.280
really, really promising.

00:21:43.280 --> 00:21:45.820
It's hard to say for sure
exactly how it's

00:21:45.820 --> 00:21:46.383
going to turn out.

00:21:46.383 --> 00:21:47.420
You know there's definitely
some rough

00:21:47.420 --> 00:21:48.500
edges right now, but--

00:21:48.500 --> 00:21:48.830
RETO MEIER: Sure.

00:21:48.830 --> 00:21:51.530
But we like the idea of beta
releases to try and figure out

00:21:51.530 --> 00:21:53.900
where you should be investing
that time and effort to get

00:21:53.900 --> 00:21:55.120
the best bang for your
buck, right?

00:21:55.120 --> 00:21:55.790
IAN NI-LEWIS: Absolutely.

00:21:55.790 --> 00:21:58.060
In fact, the only thing that
disappointed me about the beta

00:21:58.060 --> 00:22:00.120
is I couldn't get it
off of Google Play.

00:22:00.120 --> 00:22:02.200
I had to go to their
website and get it.

00:22:02.200 --> 00:22:03.650
But that's not their fault.

00:22:03.650 --> 00:22:04.500
That's probably ours.

00:22:04.500 --> 00:22:04.710
RETO MEIER: Yeah.

00:22:04.710 --> 00:22:07.760
It would be nice if we offered a
way to do a more streamlined

00:22:07.760 --> 00:22:09.850
beta release by Google
Play, but--

00:22:09.850 --> 00:22:10.450
IAN NI-LEWIS: You know what?

00:22:10.450 --> 00:22:11.480
I'll put in a request.

00:22:11.480 --> 00:22:11.980
RETO MEIER: Let's do that.

00:22:11.980 --> 00:22:12.880
I know some people.

00:22:12.880 --> 00:22:15.340
RETO MEIER: Excellent.

00:22:15.340 --> 00:22:19.390
IAN NI-LEWIS: The drawer pattern
is definitely done in,

00:22:19.390 --> 00:22:21.370
let's say, not the
wrong way, but--

00:22:21.370 --> 00:22:22.280
it's the wrong way.

00:22:22.280 --> 00:22:23.530
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:22:25.130 --> 00:22:27.080
IAN NI-LEWIS: It's not the way
that we recommend right now.

00:22:27.080 --> 00:22:30.400
And so I'd like to see
them fix that.

00:22:30.400 --> 00:22:32.560
They also have this sort of--
we didn't really touch on

00:22:32.560 --> 00:22:34.670
this, but they've got this sort
of weird thing where the

00:22:34.670 --> 00:22:38.760
drawer actually opens either to
the left or to the right,

00:22:38.760 --> 00:22:42.370
making it almost, but not
quite like a view pager.

00:22:42.370 --> 00:22:46.200
So they've sort of mixed a few
metaphors, and I think that as

00:22:46.200 --> 00:22:49.960
they sort of hone in on their
final version, they might want

00:22:49.960 --> 00:22:54.100
to take a look at that and
decide whether the user

00:22:54.100 --> 00:22:56.410
confusion is going to be worth
the benefits they're

00:22:56.410 --> 00:22:57.190
getting out of it.

00:22:57.190 --> 00:22:59.100
RETO MEIER: It's just a really
interesting example as well,

00:22:59.100 --> 00:23:01.960
where given that it is in beta,
there's an opportunity

00:23:01.960 --> 00:23:05.750
there to do some AB testing and
just sort of pick one or a

00:23:05.750 --> 00:23:07.690
few different options presented
to different users,

00:23:07.690 --> 00:23:10.260
and use analytics to figure
out which is the one that

00:23:10.260 --> 00:23:12.150
people are finding the
easiest to use?

00:23:12.150 --> 00:23:15.110
So I'm a big fan of doing that,
particularly in beta.

00:23:15.110 --> 00:23:17.360
If you've got a bunch of
alternate ideas, present them

00:23:17.360 --> 00:23:19.420
all, and see which one users
actually use and

00:23:19.420 --> 00:23:20.720
find the most intuitive.

00:23:20.720 --> 00:23:22.990
IAN NI-LEWIS: But especially
coming from their last

00:23:22.990 --> 00:23:26.330
version, which is, as I said, a
service that we used a lot.

00:23:26.330 --> 00:23:31.440
We've always enjoyed using the
app, but design wise, this is

00:23:31.440 --> 00:23:33.120
head and shoulders above
the other one.

00:23:33.120 --> 00:23:37.670
So hopefully they'll converge
onto something that everybody

00:23:37.670 --> 00:23:41.370
loves, and will get all
that figured out.

00:23:41.370 --> 00:23:43.810
The other thing, of course, and
this pretty much applies

00:23:43.810 --> 00:23:47.560
to almost any app that has any
kind of login is let's

00:23:47.560 --> 00:23:48.810
integrate that sign in.

00:23:48.810 --> 00:23:50.950
If you're not going to do with
Google, then integrate with

00:23:50.950 --> 00:23:51.880
something else.

00:23:51.880 --> 00:23:56.070
Facebook's popular, Twitter is
fine, anything where the user

00:23:56.070 --> 00:23:58.890
is likely to have an account
on the machine.

00:23:58.890 --> 00:24:02.440
For Android, we usually suggest
Google, not because

00:24:02.440 --> 00:24:06.900
that's who pays us, although
it sort of is.

00:24:06.900 --> 00:24:10.010
But because almost all Android
devices have a

00:24:10.010 --> 00:24:11.290
Google account on them.

00:24:11.290 --> 00:24:12.500
RETO MEIER: I mean, really, what
we're just trying to do

00:24:12.500 --> 00:24:15.230
is make that sign in flow as
simple as possible, and it's

00:24:15.230 --> 00:24:17.360
something that we're
particularly sensitive to,

00:24:17.360 --> 00:24:19.745
because we install
a lot of apps.

00:24:19.745 --> 00:24:23.200
And we're doing this, and the
App Clinic, obviously, we

00:24:23.200 --> 00:24:24.530
spend a fair bit of
time looking at.

00:24:24.530 --> 00:24:28.260
But we spend a lot of time
looking at a lot of apps, and

00:24:28.260 --> 00:24:29.530
we do it really quickly.

00:24:29.530 --> 00:24:32.540
We download it, we'll open it
up, and we want to figure out

00:24:32.540 --> 00:24:34.970
how this app works, what it's
doing right, what it's doing

00:24:34.970 --> 00:24:37.400
wrong, inside of 15 seconds.

00:24:37.400 --> 00:24:38.390
IAN NI-LEWIS: Well, I
don't think we're

00:24:38.390 --> 00:24:39.630
unique in that, because--

00:24:39.630 --> 00:24:40.780
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:24:40.780 --> 00:24:43.980
IAN NI-LEWIS: It's very, very
common, if a user wants to

00:24:43.980 --> 00:24:47.450
download an app for a particular
purpose, it's

00:24:47.450 --> 00:24:50.010
extremely common to download
10 of them.

00:24:50.010 --> 00:24:53.010
And the ones that are going to
get looked at first are the

00:24:53.010 --> 00:24:55.590
ones that don't throw up any
roadblocks to finding out what

00:24:55.590 --> 00:24:56.990
the functionality is.

00:24:56.990 --> 00:24:59.830
Now, Group Me is an app that
I love a lot, but I think I

00:24:59.830 --> 00:25:03.280
probably would have skipped it
at the beginning, because I

00:25:03.280 --> 00:25:07.500
couldn't get into the app until
I had not only put in my

00:25:07.500 --> 00:25:13.980
phone number, but verified it
with an SMS which I never got.

00:25:13.980 --> 00:25:17.310
Now, fortunately they've fixed
that particular flaw, but you

00:25:17.310 --> 00:25:19.930
still have to sign in before you
can get to the good stuff.

00:25:19.930 --> 00:25:20.390
RETO MEIER: Absolutely.

00:25:20.390 --> 00:25:25.720
And this is something which
actually I can see for next

00:25:25.720 --> 00:25:27.930
week, we're doing personal
fitness apps.

00:25:27.930 --> 00:25:30.190
And I actually discovered this
exact scenario where I was

00:25:30.190 --> 00:25:33.020
sitting at the foot of the
mountain, ready to go hiking,

00:25:33.020 --> 00:25:35.380
my wife's like, we should
track how far we go.

00:25:35.380 --> 00:25:36.960
I think I have an
app for that.

00:25:36.960 --> 00:25:38.280
So I fired up the [? trailer, ?]
looked at all

00:25:38.280 --> 00:25:40.270
the suggestions, and installed
each of them.

00:25:40.270 --> 00:25:43.060
And the way I chose which one to
use was I just opened them

00:25:43.060 --> 00:25:45.600
one at a time, and as soon as
I got to a roadblock, I

00:25:45.600 --> 00:25:47.210
stopped to check if the
other one was quicker.

00:25:47.210 --> 00:25:48.750
It's like, you need
me to sign in?

00:25:48.750 --> 00:25:49.000
No.

00:25:49.000 --> 00:25:50.820
You need me to do a
bunch of settings?

00:25:50.820 --> 00:25:51.680
No.

00:25:51.680 --> 00:25:54.490
And that's kind of the way
people use their apps.

00:25:54.490 --> 00:25:57.020
They're going, I need
to do something.

00:25:57.020 --> 00:25:58.560
I'm going to download an
app and see whether it

00:25:58.560 --> 00:25:59.380
does that for me.

00:25:59.380 --> 00:26:01.760
It's not the, yeah, I've
got some time.

00:26:01.760 --> 00:26:03.770
I'm going to download this app
and see what it does and see

00:26:03.770 --> 00:26:04.790
how it works.

00:26:04.790 --> 00:26:07.280
It's not really the use case
particularly on mobile.

00:26:07.280 --> 00:26:08.600
IAN NI-LEWIS: And we're being
a little unfair, because

00:26:08.600 --> 00:26:12.160
obviously, in an instant
messaging situation, you have

00:26:12.160 --> 00:26:14.340
to sign in in some way.

00:26:14.340 --> 00:26:14.910
RETO MEIER: Have an identity?

00:26:14.910 --> 00:26:18.200
IAN NI-LEWIS: But that's why
it's so important to federate

00:26:18.200 --> 00:26:21.100
or integrate with the context
manager and the account

00:26:21.100 --> 00:26:22.545
manager on the device.

00:26:22.545 --> 00:26:26.030
Now, I will say in Group Me's
favor that their new beta, if

00:26:26.030 --> 00:26:30.210
you don't sign in immediately,
still has a view pager with

00:26:30.210 --> 00:26:32.890
some demo screens on it, and
it kind of tells you what

00:26:32.890 --> 00:26:33.730
you're getting into.

00:26:33.730 --> 00:26:37.440
So I think that's a good effort,
but still, if I can

00:26:37.440 --> 00:26:40.380
just open it up and it
automatically knew,

00:26:40.380 --> 00:26:41.550
oh, you're this guy.

00:26:41.550 --> 00:26:43.150
I think I've seen you before.

00:26:43.150 --> 00:26:44.570
That would make me
super happy.

00:26:44.570 --> 00:26:45.030
RETO MEIER: Absolutely.

00:26:45.030 --> 00:26:47.360
And keep in mind as well that
even without doing the

00:26:47.360 --> 00:26:50.490
federated sign in that Ian's
describing, you can tell me

00:26:50.490 --> 00:26:53.690
what my phone number is by
checking the phone, and you

00:26:53.690 --> 00:26:55.800
can tell me what my email
address is by

00:26:55.800 --> 00:26:56.780
checking the phone.

00:26:56.780 --> 00:27:00.060
So populating those and asking
me to confirm them, rather

00:27:00.060 --> 00:27:01.870
than having me type them all
in is all things which are

00:27:01.870 --> 00:27:04.170
going to make that sign
in process smoother.

00:27:04.170 --> 00:27:05.080
IAN NI-LEWIS: Absolutely.

